def softmax(logits):
    exps = np.exp(logits)
    exp_sums = np.sum(exps, axis=1, keepdims=True)
    return exps / exp_sums

#inits
eta = 0.1
m = len(X_train)
epsilon = 1e-7
alpha = 0.1  # regularization hyperparameter 
Theta = np.random.randn(n_rows, n_col)
best_loss = float("inf") # This is useful for finding lowest values for something 
                         #this is the minimum error


for epoch in range(100001):
  #train
 logits = X_train.dot(Theta)  #Sk(X)  #(96,3)*(3,3) = (96,3)
 proba_y_train = softmax(logits)       #(96,3)
 error_train = proba_y_train - Y_train_one_hot  #(96,3)
 gradients = 1/m * X_train.T.dot(error_train) + np.r_[np.zeros([1, n_col]), alpha * Theta[1:]]
 Theta = Theta - eta * gradients

 #validation 
 logits_val = X_valid.dot(Theta)
 proba_y_valid = softmax(logits_val)
 loss_valid = -np.mean(np.sum(Y_valid_one_hot * np.log(proba_y_valid + epsilon), axis=1))
 l2_loss = 1/2 * np.sum(np.square(Theta[1:]))
 loss = loss_valid + alpha * l2_loss
 if(epoch % 500==0) : 
   print(epoch, loss)
 if loss < best_loss : 
    best_loss = loss

 else : 
   print(epoch-1,best_loss) #just before stopping
   print(epoch,loss, "  Stop at Epoch : {}  .. or the validation error will go up or flatten".format(epoch -1)) #STOP
   break

source.f74c9009:
**Prediction on validation set**

***Softmax Regression classifier prediction***

Just like the Logistic Regression classifier, the Softmax Regression classifier
predicts the class with the highest estimated probability (which is simply the
class with the highest score) 

![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)

The argmax operator returns the value of a variable that maximizes a function.
In this equation, it returns the value of k that maximizes the estimated
probability σ(s(x))

NB : $\log\left(\hat{p}_k^{(i)}\right)$ is not defined if $\hat{p}_k^{(i)} = 0$ so we will set it to a small value epsilon

cost function:

$J(\mathbf{\Theta}) = - \dfrac{1}{m}\sum\limits_{i=1}^{m}\sum\limits_{k=1}^{K}{y_k^{(i)}\log\left(\hat{p}_k^{(i)}\right)}$

gradients:

$\nabla_{\mathbf{\theta}^{(k)}} \, J(\mathbf{\Theta}) = \dfrac{1}{m} \sum\limits_{i=1}^{m}{ \left ( \hat{p}^{(i)}_k - y_k^{(i)} \right ) \mathbf{x}^{(i)}}$
